A 6-position filter wheel (IR2-FWH), of which one is for dark current measurements, holds five observing filters selected by referring to the science objectives and typical spectrum of Venus (Fig. 2). IR2-FWH/FLTR/OPT are all cooled to suppress the radiation (Table 1).
Two prominent NIR windows, the primary target of IR2, are probed with filters at 1.735 and 2.26 μm, with respective band widths of 0.043 and 0.058 μm.
To map the distribution of sub-cloud CO, the absorption band at ∼2.32μm\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\sim} 2.32\,\upmu \hbox {m}$$\end{document} is chosen. This will be differentiated with 2.26 μm (free of CO absorption) to evaluate the CO absorption index (Eq. (3); Fig. 3).
For the cloud-top altimetry, we have chosen 2.02 μm, center of a strong CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
